## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never raised; effectively dead code |

`Thread.Abort` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can interrupt `finally` blocks, leave locks held, and cause resource leaks.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Runs <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result re-wraps faulted exceptions in AggregateException,
        // matching the original throw behavior.
        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>Async overload — preferred in modern code.</summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage — Before vs. After

```csharp
// ── .NET Framework (old) ──
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ── .NET 8 (new) ──
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),   // pass token into the work
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// Or async:
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **Cancellation is cooperative** — if `work` ignores the `CancellationToken`, it keeps running after timeout. Pass the token into every I/O call (`HttpClient`, `DbCommand`, `Stream.ReadAsync`, etc.).

2. **Fire-and-forget leaks** — unlike `Thread.Abort`, the orphaned `Task` continues consuming CPU/memory until it finishes. For truly uncooperative code, isolate it in a **separate process** and kill the process on timeout.

3. **`AggregateException` unwrapping** — `task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException` (matching your original behavior). If callers expect a bare exception, use `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` instead.

4. **`Thread.ResetAbort` in catch blocks** — any `catch (ThreadAbortException)` in your codebase is now dead code. Search and remove it:
   ```bash
   grep -rn "ThreadAbortException\|Thread\.Abort\|ResetAbort" --include="*.cs"
   ```

5. **`Task.Run` uses the thread pool** — the original code created a dedicated thread. If `work` is long-running, pass `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning` to `Task.Factory.StartNew` instead to avoid starving the pool.
